{{Infobox NRHP | name = Cotting-Smith Assembly House | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes | image = Cotting-Smith Assembly House.jpg | caption = Cotting-Smith Assembly house at 138 Federal Street | location= 138 Federal St., [[Salem, Massachusetts]] | coordinates = {{coord|42|31|14.7|N|70|54|13.8|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Massachusetts#USA | area = | built = 1782 | architect = Unknown ([[Samuel McIntire]] remodel) | architecture = Federal | added = 1983 |partof = [[Federal Street District]] | governing_body = Private | refnum = 83000576 }}
Located in [[Salem, Massachusetts]] and owned by the [[Peabody Essex Museum]] the '''Cotting–Smith Assembly House''' was built in 1782 and is located at 138 Federal Street in the [[Federal Street District]]. Built as a Federalist Clubhouse in which balls, concerts, lectures, and other events might be held. [[George Washington]] attended a dance here. The original architect is unknown, but the house was later remodeled by [[Samuel McIntire]] for use as a private residence. The house is in the [[Federal architecture|Federal style]] and is listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]]. The building can be rented for special events.
