{{Merge|Olney interpretation|date=February 2018}}
The '''Olney Proclamation''' was a statement by [[United States]] [[Secretary of State]] [[Richard Olney]] in 1895 that "the United States is practically sovereign on this continent, and its [[fiat (policy debate)|fiat]] is law upon the subjects to which it confines its interposition."<ref name="Herring">{{cite book |last=Herring |first=George C. |title=From Colony to Superpower: U.S. Foreign Relations Since 1776 |page=307 |year=2008 |location=New York |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780195078220}}</ref> The statement reinforced the original purpose of the [[Monroe Doctrine]], that the U.S. had the right to intervene in its own [[Western Hemisphere|hemisphere]] and foreshadowed the events of the [[Spanish–American War]] three years later.

